California Spiny Lobster Abundance and Carapace Size - Assignment 4

Vanessa Rathbone and Nicole Schmidt

11/18/2019

INTRODUCTION

Spiny Lobster (Panulirus interruptus) are a species of special interest in California because they are a key predator in giant kelp forests. Kelp forests provide an abundance of food and coastline protection to shoreline communities. In 2012, two marine protected areas (MPAs) were established in Santa Barbara County at Naples and Isla Vista. The Santa Barbara Coastal Long Term Ecological Research Team (SBC LTER) began collecting samples at five different kelp forest research sites. Two of these sites are within MPAs (Naples and Isla Vista) and three are outside of the MPA zones (Arroyo Quemodo, Mohawk, and Carpinteria). In this report, we explore data from the SBC LTR team to analyze changes in lobster population trends, abundance, and size at MPA sites versus non-MPA sites in 2012 and 2018.

Figure 1. California spiny lobster (Panulirus interruptus). Credit: Golden State Images.

Figure 2. Spacial Coverage of the five data sites. Credit: Santa Barbara Coastal LTER, Danial C. Reed

DATA AND METHODS

The dataset includes abundance (count) and carapace size (mm) data of spiny lobster in the 5 designated sites in Santa Barbara County between 2012 and 2018. The data is collected annually by divers from October to March before the start of the lobster season. During that time, data is collected every 2-4 weeks. Our methods for observing and analyzing the data include visually exploring the data and conducting the following statistical tests: two-sided T-tests (\(\alpha\) = 0.05 throughout), mean, standard deviation, sample size, confidence intervals, p-value, and effect size. Specifically, we used these tests to infer distributions and differences across these key variables: size, count, years and sites. Analyses and figures were prepared using R software version 3.6.1.

RESULTS A: Abundance of lobsters per site

Figure 3. Abundance of spiny lobsters at 5 different SBC LTER sites between the years 2012 and 2018. Counts for lobster abundance increased for Isla Vista and Naples (both MPA sites), while Arroyo Quemado, Carpinteria, and Mohawk (non-MPA sites) have varying declines of count from 2012 to 2018. Data: Reed D. 2019.

RESULTS B: Lobster size distribution shifts in 2012 and 2018

Figure 4. Size distribution shifts of lobsters at all five sites at years 2012 and 2018 comparing changes in MPA versus non-MPA sites. The average size of lobster carapices (mm) increased for both MPA sites (IVEE and NAPL), while the non-MPA sites avaerage carpace sizes remained similar between the years.

RESULTS C: Compare mean lobster sizes (mm) at marine protected areas (MPAs) vs. non-marine protected areas (non-MPAs) in 2012 and 2018

Table 1. Lobster mean carapace sizes (mm) increased for MPA sites from 2012 to 2018, while mean carapace sizes (mm) decreased at non-MPA sites. Sample sizes increased from 231 in 2012 to 1805 in 2018.

Spiny Lobster Size (mm) Data
Year MPA Mean (mm) Standard Deviation (mm) Sample Size
2012 MPA 67.38 12.15 32
2012 non-MPA 74.92 12.41 199
2018 MPA 77.57 11.70 1244
2018 non-MPA 73.62 10.09 561

For MPA sites, between 2012 and 2018, the mean carapice size (mm) of lobsters increased by 10.2 millimeters (from 67.4 to 77.6). This size increase is statistically significant as seen in the two-sided, unpaired t-test, (t(32.5)) = -4.7, p = 0)). The effect size seen in the Cohen’s d test is large (-0.87)) indicating that from 2012 to 2018, the mean lobster carapice size increase at MPA sites is significant and substantive.

For non-MPA sites, between 2012 and 2018, the mean carapice size (mm) of lobsters decreased by 1.3 millimeters (from 74.9 to 73.6). This size increase is not statistically significant as seen in the two-sided t-test, t(296) = 1.3, p = 0). The effect size seen in the Cohen’s d test is small (0.12) indicating that from 2012 to 2018, the mean lobster size decrease at non-MPA sites is not significant or substantive.

SUMMARY
  • Lobster abundance has significantly improved since the establishment of designated MPA sites (Figure 3).
  • Mean lobster size distribution has significantly increased at MPA sites from 2012 to 2018 (Figure 5), while at non-MPA sites a decrease of mean size can be observed (Table 1).
  • We can infer from the tests used to analyze this data, that designated MPA sites increase the carapace size and abundance of spiny lobster populations more than non-MPA sites. Thus, indicating that marine protected areas allow for growth and increaed reproduction over non-protected areas.
